/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-7","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Query-Time Parameters"},"922":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-8","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","content":"A graph-based index and the go-to choice for low-latency approximate nearest neighbor search — delivering state-of-the-art speed and recall at the cost of higher memory usage"},"923":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-9","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"HNSW builds a multi-layer graph structure where each node represents a vector and edges connect nodes based on similarity."},"924":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-10","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Layers form a hierarchy 🪜"},"925":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-11","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Upper layers are sparse and act as \"highways\" for fast long-range navigation."},"926":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-12","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Lower layers are dense and provide fine-grained local neighborhood connectivity."},"927":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-13","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"How search works (coarse → fine) 🔍"},"928":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-14","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Start from an entry point at the top layer."},"929":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-15","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"At the current layer, you greedily walk to neighbors that are closer to the query vector, until you can't get any closer."},"930":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-16","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Then you drop down one layer at that position and repeat the same greedy search."},"931":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-17","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"On the lowest layer, this process is done more carefully (with a small candidate list) to refine the result."},"932":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-18","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Why this is fast and accurate ⚡ 🎯"},"933":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-19","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Fast: Upper layers let you jump quickly to the right region without visiting most points."},"934":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-20","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#how-it-works","content":"Accurate: The dense bottom layer lets you explore the local neighborhood thoroughly, so recall stays high."},"935":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-21","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#when-to-use-an-hnsw-index","content":"✅ Real-time, low-latency applications (e.g., conversational AI and live recommendations)"},"936":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-22","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#when-to-use-an-hnsw-index","content":"✅ Production systems requiring consistent high recall with minimal latency"},"937":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-23","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#when-to-use-an-hnsw-index","content":"className: text-base"},"938":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-24","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#when-to-use-an-hnsw-index","content":"type: idea"},"939":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-25","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#when-to-use-an-hnsw-index","content":"Best Practice: HNSW is our recommended default for most production use cases. It strikes an excellent balance between speed, accuracy, and robustness."},"940":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-26","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#advantages","content":"✨ Near-logarithmic query time — Typically O(log n) for large datasets"},"941":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-27","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#advantages","content":"✨ Consistently high recall across diverse data distributions"},"942":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-28","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#advantages","content":"✨ Faster indexing than many alternatives (e.g., IVF-based methods)"},"943":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-29","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#trade-offs","content":"⚠️ Higher memory footprint — Graph links require additional storage (scales with m)"},"944":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-30","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#trade-offs","content":"⚠️ Indexing complexity of O(n log n) — Slower build time than Flat index (but often faster than IVF)"},"945":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-31","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#key-parameters","content":"className: text-base"},"946":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-32","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#key-parameters","content":"type: idea"},"947":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-33","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#key-parameters","content":"Tuning Tip:Start with defaults, then adjust ef first for recall/latency trade-offs.Only if needed, increase ef_construction or m for better accuracy — but expect slower indexing and higher memory use."},"948":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-34","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Parameter"},"949":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-35","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Description"},"950":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-36","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Tuning Guidance"},"951":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-37","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"metric_type"},"952":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-38","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Similarity metric used to compare vectors"},"953":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-39","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Choose based on how your embeddings were trained"},"954":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-40","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"m"},"955":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-41","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Max neighbors per node — The maximum number of bidirectional links created for each node during graph construction"},"956":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-42","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"• Higher m →  ✨ better recall and graph connectivity  ⚠️ more memory usage and higher latency for both indexing and search"},"957":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-43","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"ef_construction"},"958":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-44","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Index-time candidate pool size — Determines how many neighboring candidates the algorithm considers when inserting a new vector into the graph"},"959":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-45","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"• Higher ef_construction →  ✨ better graph quality and higher recall  ⚠️ longer index build time (does not affect query speed)"},"960":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-46","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"quantize_type"},"961":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-47","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Vector quantization method to apply  Defaults to no quantization"},"962":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-48","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#index-time-parameters","content":"See Quantization for more details"},"963":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-49","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Parameter"},"964":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-50","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Description"},"965":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-51","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Tuning Guidance"},"966":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-52","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"ef"},"967":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-53","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Query-time candidate pool size — Determines how many potential neighbors are explored at each step during graph traversal at query time"},"968":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-54","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"• Higher ef →  ✨ higher recall  ⚠️ higher query latency"},"969":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-55","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"radius"},"970":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-56","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Distance (similarity) threshold for range-based filtering — only documents satisfying the threshold are returned"},"971":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-57","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Example:  • With inner product MetricType.IP, set radius=0.6 to  keep only results with score > 0.6  ✅ Use when: You want to filter out low-quality matches  🚫 Skip when: You want all top-k results, regardless of quality"},"972":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-58","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"is_linear"},"973":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-59","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Forces a brute-force linear search instead of using the index"},"974":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-60","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"🐌 Very slow for large datasets!  ✅ Only use for: Debugging, tiny collections, or verifying index accuracy"},"975":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-61","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"is_using_refiner"},"976":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-62","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Enables exact score refinement (recomputes exact similarity scores) for top candidates — useful when vectors are quantized"},"977":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index-63","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/hnsw-index#query-time-parameters","content":"✅ Turn on: When you need higher accuracy  ⚠️ Adds latency due to exact re-scoring"},"978":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","type":"page","content":"Vector Index","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Introduction","Concepts","Vector Index"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index"},"979":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-0","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#approximate-vs-exact-search","content":"Approximate vs. Exact Search"},"980":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-1","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"Recall: Measuring Approximation Quality"},"981":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-2","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"Vector Index Types"},"982":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-3","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","content":"A vector index is a specialized data structure that accelerates similarity search over large collections of vector embeddings."},"983":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-4","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","content":"Without an index, finding the most similar items to a query requires comparing it against every single vector in the database — a process known as brute-force or flat search."},"984":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-5","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","content":"Brute-force search is:"},"985":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-6","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","content":"✅ Accurate: Returns the exact most similar results — no approximation."},"986":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-7","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","content":"⚠️ Painfully slow at scale: With millions or billions of vectors, queries can take seconds or minutes, making them impractical for real-time applications."},"987":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-8","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#approximate-vs-exact-search","content":"Most vector indexes use Approximate Nearest Neighbor (ANN) algorithms."},"988":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-9","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#approximate-vs-exact-search","content":"Instead of finding the exact closest matches, ANN finds very close approximations — often indistinguishable in quality for practical purposes — while delivering massive gains in speed and efficiency."},"989":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-10","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#approximate-vs-exact-search","content":"For real-world uses, such as semantic search or recommendations, this small accuracy trade-off delivers huge gains in speed and scalability. In short: good enough to be correct, but lightning fast ✨."},"990":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-11","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"Recall is the standard metric for evaluating how well an ANN algorithm preserves result quality."},"991":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-12","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"It quantifies the fraction of true nearest neighbors — identified by an exact (brute-force) search — that appear in the top‑k results returned by the approximate method:"},"992":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-13","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"Example:"},"993":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-14","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"If you request the top 10 results and 9 of them match the true top 10 from a brute-force search, your recall@10 is 90%."},"994":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-15","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"High recall (e.g., ≥ 96%) typically means the approximation is practically indistinguishable from exact search for most applications."},"995":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-16","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#recall-measuring-approximation-quality","content":"Different index types (e.g., HNSW) and their parameters (e.g., ef_search) let you fine-tune the balance between recall, query speed, and resource usage — so you can optimize for your specific accuracy and performance requirements."},"996":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-17","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"Zvec supports three vector index types, each suited to different use cases, dataset sizes, and performance requirements:"},"997":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-18","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"Flat (Brute-Force) index"},"998":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-19","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"HNSW (Hierarchical Navigable Small World)"},"999":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-20","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"IVF (Inverted File Index)"},"1000":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-21","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"className: text-base"},"1001":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-22","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"type: idea"},"1002":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index-23","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index#vector-index-types","content":"Choose an index type based on your scale, latency requirements, and accuracy tolerance. Always use the same distance metric that your embedding model was trained for."},"1003":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"page","content":"IVF Index","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Introduction","Concepts","Vector Index"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index"},"1004":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-0","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","content":"Inverted File Index"},"1005":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-1","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#how-it-works","content":"How It Works"},"1006":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-2","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#indexing-phase-️","content":"Indexing Phase ⚙️"},"1007":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-3","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-phase-","content":"Query Phase 🔍"},"1008":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-4","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"When to Use an IVF Index"},"1009":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-5","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#advantages","content":"Advantages"},"1010":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-6","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#trade-offs","content":"Trade-offs"},"1011":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-7","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#key-parameters","content":"Key Parameters"},"1012":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-8","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Index-Time Parameters"},"1013":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-9","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Query-Time Parameters"},"1014":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-10","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","content":"A partition-based, scalable, memory-efficient indexing method best suited for large datasets — especially those with natural cluster structure — at the expense of slower indexing and more involved tuning"},"1015":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-11","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#how-it-works","content":"IVF operates by partitioning the entire vector space into clusters. The number of clusters is controlled by the parameter n_list (short for \"number of lists\")."},"1016":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-12","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#indexing-phase-️","content":"Clustering: The algorithm first applies a clustering algorithm, creating n_list clusters. Each cluster is represented by its centroid — a central point that best represents all vectors assigned to that cluster."},"1017":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-13","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#indexing-phase-️","content":"Assignment: Each vector in the dataset is assigned to the cluster whose centroid is closest to it. The vector is then stored in an inverted list (also called a \"bucket\") associated with that centroid. The index essentially becomes a mapping from centroids to their associated vectors."},"1018":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-14","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-phase-","content":"Centroid Selection: When a query vector arrives, the system first computes distances between the query and all n_list centroids to identify the n_probe nearest centroids (n_probe is a parameter that controls how many centroids to consider)."},"1019":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-15","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-phase-","content":"Local Search: Instead of scanning the entire dataset of N vectors, the search is restricted to only the vectors stored in the n_probe selected buckets. A brute-force (or refined) search is then performed within those buckets to find the final nearest neighbors."},"1020":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-16","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"✅ Your vector dataset exhibits natural clustering or locality structure"},"1021":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-17","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"✅ You’re working with very large datasets and memory efficiency is critical"},"1022":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-18","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"✅ You need to tune parameters to achieve optimal performance"},"1023":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-19","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"className: text-base"},"1024":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-20","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"type: idea"},"1025":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-21","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"Best Practice:"},"1026":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-22","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"IVF works best on datasets with inherent clustering structure."},"1027":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-23","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"For even greater memory efficiency and scalability, combine it with Product Quantization (PQ)."},"1028":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-24","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#when-to-use-an-ivf-index","content":"The performance of IVF is highly sensitive to parameters like n_list. As such, IVF is best suited for practitioners who can systematically experiment with, validate, and optimize these settings for their specific data distribution and latency-recall requirements."},"1029":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-25","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#advantages","content":"✨ Compatibility — Often used as a base layer in composite indexes (e.g., IVF-PQ) for further optimization"},"1030":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-26","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#advantages","content":"✨ Scalability — Query time scales approximately as O(N / n_list × n_probe), making it highly efficient for large N when n_list is large and n_probe is small"},"1031":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-27","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#advantages","content":"✨ Memory Efficiency — Stores vectors in compact inverted lists with minimal overhead from centroids and list pointers, typically uses significantly less memory than graph-based methods like HNSW"},"1032":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-28","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#trade-offs","content":"⚠️ Indexing Overhead — Building the index requires clustering, which can be computationally intensive and slower to build than indexes like HNSW"},"1033":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-29","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#trade-offs","content":"⚠️ Parameter Sensitivity — Accuracy and latency are highly dependent on the choice of n_list and n_probe"},"1034":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-30","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Parameter"},"1035":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-31","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Description"},"1036":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-32","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Tuning Guidance"},"1037":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-33","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"metric_type"},"1038":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-34","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Similarity metric used to compare vectors"},"1039":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-35","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Choose based on how your embeddings were trained"},"1040":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-36","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"n_list"},"1041":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-37","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Number of clusters (inverted lists) — the vector space is partitioned into this many clusters during indexing"},"1042":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-38","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"• Start with n_list ≈ \\sqrt{N}, where N is the number of vectors  • Larger n_list → ✨ finer partitioning, smaller buckets, faster search — but ⚠️ higher indexing cost and more centroids to manage  • Smaller n_list → ✨ faster index construction — but ⚠️ larger buckets and slower search"},"1043":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-39","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"n_iters"},"1044":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-40","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Centroid refinement iterations — number of passes to optimize cluster centroids during indexing"},"1045":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-41","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"• Higher n_iters →  ✨ better clustering quality  ⚠️ longer index build time"},"1046":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-42","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"quantize_type"},"1047":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-43","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"Vector quantization method to apply  Defaults to no quantization"},"1048":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-44","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#index-time-parameters","content":"See Quantization for more details"},"1049":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-45","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Parameter"},"1050":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-46","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Description"},"1051":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-47","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Tuning Guidance"},"1052":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-48","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"n_probe"},"1053":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-49","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Number of clusters to search at query time — the system retrieves candidates only from these nearest clusters."},"1054":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-50","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"• Higher n_probe →  ✨ higher recall  ⚠️ slower queries"},"1055":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-51","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"radius"},"1056":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-52","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Distance (similarity) threshold for range-based filtering — only documents satisfying the threshold are returned"},"1057":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-53","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Example: With inner product metric MetricType.IP, set radius=0.6 to  keep only results with score > 0.6  ✅ Use when: You want to filter out low-quality matches  🚫 Skip when: You want all top-k results, regardless of quality"},"1058":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-54","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"is_linear"},"1059":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-55","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"Forces a brute-force linear search instead of using the index"},"1060":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index-56","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/ivf-index#query-time-parameters","content":"🐌 Very slow for large datasets!  ✅ Only use for: Debugging, tiny collections, or verifying index accuracy"},"1061":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"page","content":"Quantization","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Introduction","Concepts","Vector Index"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization"},"1062":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-0","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#storage-behavior","content":"Storage Behavior"},"1063":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-1","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#enabling-quantization","content":"Enabling Quantization"},"1064":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-2","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#quantization-types","content":"Quantization Types"},"1065":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-3","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#fp16-half-precision-floating-point","content":"FP16 (Half-Precision Floating Point)"},"1066":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-4","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#int8-8-bit-integer-quantization","content":"INT8 (8-Bit Integer Quantization)"},"1067":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-5","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#int4-4-bit-integer-quantization","content":"INT4 (4-Bit Integer Quantization)"},"1068":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-6","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"Quantization is a compression technique that transforms vectors from their original (specifically FP32) format into a more compact representation, reducing the size of vector indexes used for search."},"1069":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-7","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"This transformation approximates vectors using fewer bits per dimension — enabling:"},"1070":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-8","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"✨ Lower memory footprint — especially when the index is memory-resident,"},"1071":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-9","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"✨ Faster I/O and lower query latency — due to reduced data movement and efficient integer/fp16 arithmetic,"},"1072":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-10","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"✨ Better scalability on resource-constrained hardware."},"1073":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-11","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"className: text-base"},"1074":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-12","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"type: warn"},"1075":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-13","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"Important:"},"1076":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-14","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"Quantization is a lossy and irreversible compression method. It improves runtime efficiency at the cost of potentially reduced recall accuracy. Always validate its effect on your retrieval quality."},"1077":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-15","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","content":"Quantization only provides benefits when applied to vectors in a FP32 format."},"1078":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-16","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#storage-behavior","content":"To ensure data integrity and flexibility, Zvec stores both the original vectors and their quantized versions. This means:"},"1079":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-17","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#storage-behavior","content":"The overall on-disk storage usage may increase (due to storing two copies)."},"1080":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-18","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#storage-behavior","content":"However, only the quantized vectors are loaded into memory for indexing and search, significantly reducing the active index size."},"1081":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-19","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#storage-behavior","content":"Users can always retrieve the original, unaltered vectors when needed."},"1082":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-20","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#enabling-quantization","content":"You can activate quantization when creating a vector index in Zvec by specifying the desired quantization type (FP16, INT8, or INT4) through the quantize_type parameter in your VectorSchema."},"1083":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-21","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#enabling-quantization","content":"Zvec will then automatically generate and manage the quantized representation alongside your original vectors."},"1084":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-22","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#fp16-half-precision-floating-point","content":"Uses 16-bit floating-point numbers to reduce memory footprint and accelerate computation while maintaining high numerical precision. Ideal for applications requiring near-FP32 accuracy with improved efficiency. Requires conversion from FP32 source."},"1085":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-23","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#int8-8-bit-integer-quantization","content":"Represents vectors using 8-bit integers, significantly reducing storage and memory bandwidth requirements. Offers a good trade-off between speed, size, and retrieval accuracy for many similarity search tasks. Requires conversion from FP32 source."},"1086":{"id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization-24","page_id":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/en/docs/concepts/vector-index/quantization#int4-4-bit-integer-quantization","content":"Ultra-compact representation using only 4 bits per dimension. Maximizes storage density and inference speed, suitable for latency-sensitive or resource-constrained environments where noticeable accuracy loss is acceptable. Requires conversion from FP32 source."},"1087":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"page","content":"Conditional Filtering","breadcrumbs":["User Guide","Working with Data","Data Operations","Query"],"tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter"},"1088":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter-0","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter#performance-considerations","content":"Performance Considerations"},"1089":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter-1","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter#prerequisites","content":"Prerequisites"},"1090":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter-2","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter#performing-conditional-filtering","content":"Performing Conditional Filtering"},"1091":{"id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter-3","page_id":"/en/docs/data-operations/query/filter","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/en/docs/data-operat